Looking at this theorem, I need to prove that inserting the same element `elt` into two permuted lists `l1` and `l2` (at potentially different indices) results in permuted lists.

The key insight is that `List.Perm` is an equivalence relation that means two lists contain the same elements with the same multiplicities, regardless of order. If `l1.Perm l2`, then inserting the same element into both lists should preserve this permutation relationship.

The proof can use the fact that `List.Perm` is preserved under insertion operations, and we can use `List.Perm.cons` or similar lemmas from the standard library.

```lean
theorem list_Perm_insertIdx {l1 l2 : List α} {hPerm : l1.Perm l2}
    {idx1 idx2 : Nat} {hidx1 : idx1 <= l1.length} {hidx2 : idx2 <= l2.length} {elt : α} :
    (l1.insertIdx idx1 elt).Perm (l2.insertIdx idx2 elt) := by
  apply List.Perm.trans
  · exact List.perm_insertIdx _ _ _
  · apply List.Perm.trans
    · exact List.Perm.cons _ hPerm
    · exact (List.perm_insertIdx _ _ _).symm
```
